article.headline: Bird scores 21 points, adds 10 assist for hot Storm
article.linkText: Storm send Mystics to eighth consecutive loss
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle coach Ann Donovan wasn't happy that the Storm were outplayed for 20 minutes by the league's worst team. So she let them hear about it at halftime. Seattle responded in the second half and pulled out a 76-72 victory over the Washington Mystics on Thursday night. Sue Bird scored 16 of her points in the second half, and seven in the opening three minutes, as the Storm (9-6) won for the ninth time in 12 games and improved their home record to 5-2. "Coach Donovan definitely challenged us at halftime," said Bird, who also had 10 assists. "You could tell she was pretty upset." Fellow All-Star Lauren Jackson scored 25 for the Storm, who needed a late spurt to hold on. Kamila Vodichkova had 12 and Sandy Brondello added 10 for Seattle. Chamique Holdsclaw had 21 points and 10 rebounds and Coco Miller scored 20 points for Washington (2-11), which lost its eighth consecutive game. Seattle trailed 68-67 with 2:52 to play before Bird hit a 3-pointer and found Vodichkova alone under the basket for a layup and a 72-68 lead. Asjha Jones cut the lead to 72-70 when she made a layup and was fouled with 1:15 left. Jones missed the free throw and Seattle got the rebound, forcing Washington to foul Bird. She hit four straight free throws before Holdsclaw made a layup with less than 10 seconds left for Washington's final points. "Sue got it together totally in the second half," Donovan said. "If she couldn't get to the basket, she was getting to the foul line. If she wasn't getting to the foul line, she was making incredible assists." Jones and Stacey Dales-Schumann added 12 each for the Mystics. "There are a lot of positives," Mystics coach Marianne Stanley said. "My team was hungry. They played hard and shot the ball the way we're capable of shooting it. I'm hurting for them right now because we were right there, knocking on the door." Washington controlled play in the first half and led 37-26 with 1:13 left in the half. Seattle clawed back with a 6-0 run and went to halftime down 37-32.

Game notes
Jackson has led Seattle in scoring in 11 of the 14 games she has played. ... Holdsclaw scored a career-high 32 points against Seattle last season. ... Seattle is 2-3 all time against Washington. ... Bird will start her second straight WNBA All-Star game on July 12. ... Holdsclaw, who missed six games with a hamstring injury, leads the league in rebounding.
